  <h2>Memory vs Storage</h2>
  <p>
    Computers have two very different places to keep information: <strong>RAM (Memory)</strong> and <strong>Storage (Hard Drive/SSD)</strong>. They do different jobs!
  </p>

  <h2>RAM — Short-Term Memory</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>RAM</strong> stands for <strong>Random Access Memory</strong>. Think of it like your desk — it holds the things you're working on <em>right now</em>. It's super fast but temporary — when you turn off the computer, everything in RAM disappears!
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>⚡ Very fast — the CPU can read from RAM instantly.</li>
    <li>🔌 Temporary — clears when power is off.</li>
    <li>📏 Usually 8GB to 32GB in modern computers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Hard Drive / SSD — Long-Term Storage</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>Hard Drive (HDD)</strong> or <strong>Solid State Drive (SSD)</strong> is like your closet — it stores everything permanently: your photos, games, documents, and the operating system itself.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🐢 Slower than RAM (but SSDs are much faster than old HDDs).</li>
    <li>📁 Permanent — files stay even when powered off.</li>
    <li>📦 Usually 256GB to several Terabytes in modern computers.</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    RAM = your desk (quick, temporary workspace). Hard Drive = your bookshelf (permanent, long-term storage).
  </blockquote>

